    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i have a physics exam coming up and i'm struggling a bit with the concept of quantum entanglement. can you give me a concise, non-mathematical summary of what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a bizarre, yet fascinating, concept where two or more particles become linked in such a way that they share the same fate, no matter how far apart they are. Imagine two perfectly matched, yet utterly unpredictable, magical coins—if one lands heads, you instantly know the other is tails, even if it's across the galaxy. The key difference from classical correlation is that in the quantum world, the properties of those particles *don't* have a definite state until one of them is actually measured. Before measurement, they exist in a fuzzy, probabilistic state, like a cloud of potential outcomes, which is much weirder than just having two pre-set, correlated marbles in separate bags.",
