    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "the coin thing makes sense but it still feels a bit hand-wavy. you mentioned it's \"weird\" and \"unpredictable\"—Einstein called it \"spooky action at a distance\" because it seems to defy how things should work. can you explain why it's considered so \"spooky\" or counterintuitive compared to normal physics?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It's spooky because it seems to violate the cosmic speed limit—the speed of light—which is a cornerstone of our normal, classical understanding of the universe. When you measure one entangled particle, its partner instantly assumes a corresponding state, faster than any signal could possibly travel between them. This instantaneous connection is what makes Einstein so uncomfortable; he felt it implied some hidden, local mechanism must be at play, like a secret message being passed between the particles. It's as if the particles are communicating faster than the fastest messenger in the entire known universe, which is frankly, a bit like a tiny, hyper-efficient, and deeply suspicious network of communication running through the very fabric of reality.",
